<section class="article-title">
    <h1>Protein and Performance</h1>
    <h2>Why, When, and How Much to Eat</h2>
</section>

<section class="article-section">
    <div class="article-text">
        <h2>Why Protein Is Essential</h2>
        <p>
            Every time you exercise, especially with resistance or impact, you create tiny tears in your muscle fibers.
            Protein provides the amino acids needed to repair those tears helping you build stronger, more resilient muscle.
            Without enough protein, training results stall, recovery slows, and injury risk increases.
        </p>

        <h2>Protein 101</h2>
        <p>How Much Do You Really Need?</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Recreational athletes:</strong> 1.2–1.6g/kg body weight</li>
            <li><strong>Endurance athletes:</strong> 1.4–1.8g/kg</li>
            <li><strong>Strength athletes:</strong> 1.6–2.2g/kg</li>
        </ul>
        <p>For a 70kg person:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Moderate training:</strong> ~100g protein/day</li>
            <li><strong>Heavy strength training:</strong> ~140g/day</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Where to Get Your Protein</h2>
        <p>Complete sources (ideal for athletes):</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Chicken, turkey, beef, eggs, dairy, soy, quinoa, fish</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Plant-based combinations:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Lentils + rice</li>
            <li>Hummus + whole wheat pita</li>
            <li>Peanut butter + whole grain bread</li>
        </ul>
        <p><em>Don’t rely on one food—variety ensures a full amino acid profile.</em></p>

        <h2>Timing & Distribution</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Spread protein throughout the day (every 3–4 hours)</li>
            <li>After training: aim for 20–40g within 1 hour to maximize muscle repair</li>
            <li>Before bed: a slow-digesting protein like casein (e.g., Greek yogurt) can aid overnight recovery</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Sample Daily Protein Plan (for 140g goal)</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Breakfast:</strong> Oats + whey + almonds = 30g</li>
            <li><strong>Lunch:</strong> Grilled salmon + quinoa + greens = 35g</li>
            <li><strong>Snack:</strong> Protein smoothie + banana = 25g</li>
            <li><strong>Dinner:</strong> Chicken stir-fry + rice = 35g</li>
            <li><strong>Bedtime:</strong> Cottage cheese = 15g</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Myths to Avoid</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>"You can only absorb 30g per meal"</strong> – False. Your body digests and utilizes protein as needed.</li>
            <li><strong>"More protein = more muscle"</strong> – Only if paired with progressive resistance training.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

